{{Infobox hotel | hotel_name = Fairmont Monte Carlo | image= |caption= | pushpin_map = Monaco | location = 12, Avenue des Spélugues 98000 [[Monte Carlo]] | opening_date = 20 August 1975 | architect = Jean Ginsberg, Jean and José Notari, and Herbert Weisskamp | developer = [[Caroli Group]] | operator = [[Fairmont Hotels and Resorts]] | number_of_rooms = 602 | number_of_suites = 30 | number_of_restaurants = 3 | floors = 7 | website = [http://www.fairmont.com/monte-carlo/ www.fairmont.com] | coordinates = {{coord|43.7403908|7.4291987|display=inline}} }}
The '''Fairmont Monte Carlo''' is a luxury resort located in [[Monte Carlo]] managed by the Canadian-based hotel chain [[Fairmont Hotels and Resorts]].
==History== Construction of the hotel was completed in the early 1970s. The hotel was built on the spot of the first Monegasque railway station, by the real estate development company [[Caroli Group]].<ref name="groupecaroli">[http://caroli-realestate.com/fr/presentation Groupe Caroli: Presentation]</ref> As it stands today,{{when|date=January 2018}} there is still a section of the original station wall hidden in one of the hotel's offices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotel-fairmont-monaco.federal-hotel.com/page_en_1.html| title=Hôtel Fairmont Monte Carlo - History |accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref> Instead of building the hotel up the rocks, the property is partially built into the Mediterranean coast. The hotel started under the name of Loews Hotel Monte-Carlo and opened in August 1975. In 1998, [[Toufic Aboukhater]] bought the hotel from Loews Hotels Holding Corporation for an undisclosed price and renamed it the Monte Carlo Grand Hotel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotel-online.com/archive/archive-49516 |title=Hotel Online Special Report - Loews Monte Carlo Hotel Sold |accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref>
In 2004 the hotel was acquired by hotel chain [[Fairmont Hotels and Resorts]] for 215 million euro.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forsters.co.uk/index.php?page=60&content=229| title=Unwritten law - The message: Agreements between friends should be recorded in writing to ensure they are enforceable. |accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref> It was the first purchase by a joint venture of Fairmont, Kingdom Hotels International and Bank of Scotland Corporate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1030561/000114420404022498/v010272_ex99-1.htm |title=SEC.gov: Fairmont, Kingdom and Bank of Scotland Launch European-Focused Joint Venture |accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref> After acquiring the hotel, the complex was renamed Fairmont Monte Carlo. A renovation project began in 2005 and in 2009 the hotel began its second round of renovations.
During the annual Formula 1 racing event on [[Circuit de Monaco]], the racers make use of the tunnel under the hotel<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldtravelimages.net/Monaco_Montecarlo.html | title=The most famous part of Monaco, that gave name to the famous Monte Carlo rally |accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref> which is considered{{by who|date=January 2018}} one of the most dangerous parts of the circuit. One of the corners is still{{when|date=January 2018}} named after the previous hotel name, the Grand Hotel.
