{{Infobox airport | name = Ratanakiri Airport | nativename = | image = | IATA = RBE | ICAO = VDRK | pushpin_map = Cambodia | pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport in Cambodia | pushpin_label = VDRK | pushpin_label_position = left | type = Public | owner = | operator = | city-served = [[Ratanakiri Province]], [[Cambodia]] | location = [[Ban Lung]] | elevation-f = | elevation-m = | coordinates = {{coord|13|43|55|N|106|59|01|E|region:KH_type:airport|display=inline,title}} | website = | metric-rwy = y | r1-number = 18/36 | r1-length-m = 1,300 | r1-length-f = | r1-surface = | stat-year = ? | stat1-header = Passenger movements | stat1-data = ? | stat2-header = Airfreight movements in tonnes | stat2-data = ? | stat3-header = Aircraft movements | stat3-data = ? | footnotes = }}
'''Ratanakiri Airport''' {{airport codes|RBE<ref>{{GCM|RBE}}</ref>|VDRK}} is an [[airport]] in [[Ban Lung]] town in [[Ratanakiri Province]], [[Cambodia]].<ref>''Location Indicators.'' ICAO Doc 7910/128, June 2008.</ref>
== History == In November 2005, there was a minor accident at Ratanakiri Airport when a plane arriving from [[Phnom Penh]] hit the side of the runway and ground looped, which caused the right hand main landing gear to collapse. The [[Antonov An-24|Y-7]]-100C aircraft was operated by [[PMT Air]] and leased from [[Royal Phnom Penh Airways]]. There were 59 passengers and 6 crew aboard at the time of the crash, but there were no fatalities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20051121-0|title=Accident description|accessdate=2009-01-10}}</ref> In the wake of this incident, and the more serious crash of [[PMTair Flight 241]] in [[Kampot Province|Kampot]] in July, PMT Air ceased regular commercial flights to Ratanakiri. Since then, no commercial flights to Ban Lung are available and only chartered and private flights use the airport.
